class are likely to change in future releases.","pos":[2518,2626]},{"content":"All control bar objects/windows will be child windows of some parent frame window.","pos":[2633,2715]},{"content":"They are usually added as a sibling to the client area of the frame (for example, an MDI Client or view).","pos":[2716,2821]},{"content":"The child window ID of a control bar is important.","pos":[2822,2872]},{"content":"The default layout of control bar only works for control bars with IDs in the range of <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>AFX_IDW_CONTROLBAR_FIRST<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> to <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>AFX_IDW_CONTROLBAR_LAST<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>.","pos":[2873,3020],"source":" The default layout of control bar only works for control bars with IDs in the range of **AFX_IDW_CONTROLBAR_FIRST** to **AFX_IDW_CONTROLBAR_LAST**."},{"content":"Note that even though there is a range of 256 control bar IDs, the first 32 of these control bar IDs are special since they are directly supported by the print preview architecture.","pos":[3021,3202]},{"pos":[3209,3267],"content":"The <ph id=\"ph1\">`CControlBar`</ph> class gives standard implementation for:","source":"The `CControlBar` class gives standard implementation for:"},{"content":"Aligning the control bar to the top, bottom, or either side of the frame.","pos":[3277,3350]},{"content":"Allocating control item arrays.","pos":[3360,3391]},{"content":"Supporting the implementation of derived classes.","pos":[3401,3450]},{"content":"C++ control bar objects will usually be embedded as members of a <ph id=\"ph1\">`CFrameWnd`</ph> derived class, and will be cleaned up when the parent <ph id=\"ph2\">`HWND`</ph> and object are destroyed.","pos":[3457,3620],"source":"C++ control bar objects will usually be embedded as members of a `CFrameWnd` derived class, and will be cleaned up when the parent `HWND` and object are destroyed."},{"content":"If you need to allocate a control bar object on the heap, you can simply set the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt