/bpt>WM_SIZEPARENT<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> to all children in the control bar range.","pos":[4368,4460],"source":" The frame window sends a message **WM_SIZEPARENT** to all children in the control bar range."},{"content":"Along with this message, a pointer to the parent's client rectangle is passed.","pos":[4461,4539]},{"content":"This message is sent to children in Z-order.","pos":[4540,4584]},{"content":"The control-bar children use this information to position themselves and to decrease the size of the parent's client area.","pos":[4585,4707]},{"content":"The final rectangle that is left for the normal client area (less control bars) is used to position the main client window (usually an MDI client, view or splitter window).","pos":[4708,4880]},{"pos":[4887,4961],"content":"See <ph id=\"ph1\">`CWnd::RepositionBars`</ph> and <ph id=\"ph2\">`CFrameWnd::RecalcLayout`</ph> for more details.","source":"See `CWnd::RepositionBars` and `CFrameWnd::RecalcLayout` for more details."},{"pos":[4968,5117],"content":"MFC private Windows messages, including <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>WM_SIZEPARENT<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, are documented in <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Technical Note 24<ept id=\"p2\">](../mfc/tn024-mfc-defined-messages-and-resources.md)</ept>.","source":"MFC private Windows messages, including **WM_SIZEPARENT**, are documented in [Technical Note 24](../mfc/tn024-mfc-defined-messages-and-resources.md)."},{"pos":[5163,5173],"content":"CStatusBar"},{"content":"A status bar is a control bar that has a row of text output panes.","pos":[5180,5246]},{"content":"There are two common ways to use text output panes:","pos":[5247,5298]},{"content":"As a message line","pos":[5308,5325]},{"content":"(for example, the standard menu help message line).","pos":[5336,5387]},{"content":"These are usually accessed by a 0-based indexed","pos":[5388,5435]},{"content":"As status indicators","pos":[5445,5465]},{"content":"(for example, the CAP, NUM and SCRL indicators).","pos":[5476,5524]},{"content":"These are usually accessed by string/command ID.","pos":[5525,5573]},{"content":"The font for the status bar is 10-point MS Sans Serif (dictated by the Windows Interface Application Design Guide or the font mappers best match of a 10-point Swiss proportional font).","pos":[5580,5764]},{"content":"On certain versions of Windows, such as the Japanese edition, the fonts selected are different.","pos":[5765,5860]},{"content":"The colors used in the status bar are also consistent with the recommendation of the Windows Interface Application Design Guide.","pos":[5867,5995]},{"content":"These colors are not hard coded and are changed dynamically in response to user customization in Control Panel.","pos":[5996,6107]},{"content":"Item","pos":[6114,6118]},{"content":"Windows COLOR value","pos":[6119,6138]},{"content":"Default RGB","pos":[6139,6150]},{"content":"Status bar background","pos":[6214,6235]},{"content":"COLOR_BTNFACE","pos":[6238,6251]},{"content":"RGB(192, 192, 192)","pos":[6254,6272]},{"content":"Status bar text","pos":[6277,6292]},{"content":"COLOR_BTNTEXT","pos":[6295,6308]},{"content":"RGB(000, 000, 000)","pos":[6311,6329]},{"content":"Status bar top/left edges","pos":[6334,6359]},{"content":"COLOR_BTNHIGHLIGHT","pos":[6362,6380]},{"content":"RGB(255, 255, 255)","pos":[6383,6401]},{"content":"Status bar bot/right edges","pos":[6406,6432]},{"content":"COLOR_BTNSHADOW","pos":[6435,6450]},{"content":"RGB(128, 128, 128)","pos":[6453,6471]},{"content":"CCmdUI Support for CStatusBar","pos":[6481,6510]},{"content":"The way indicators are usually updated is through the <ph id=\"ph1\">`ON_UPDATE_COMMAND_UI`</ph> mechanism.","pos":[6519,6606],"source":"The way indicators are usually updated is through the `ON_UPDATE_COMMAND_UI` mechanism."},{"content":"On idle time, the status bar will call the <ph id=\"ph1\">`ON_UPDATE_COMMAND_UI`</ph> handler with the string ID of the indicator pane.","pos":[6607,6722],"source":" On idle time, the status bar will call the `ON_UPDATE_COMMAND_UI` handler with the string ID of the indicator pane."},{"pos":[6729,6773],"content":"The <ph id=\"ph1\">`ON_UPDATE_COMMAND_UI`</ph> handler can call:","source":"The `ON_UPDATE_COMMAND_UI` handler can call:"},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Enable<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>: To enable or disable the pane.","pos":[6781,6823],"source":"**Enable**: To enable or disable the pane."},{"content":"A disabled pane looks exactly like an enabled pane but the text is invisible (that is, turns off the text indicator).","pos":[6824,6941]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>SetText<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>: To change the text.","pos":[6949,6981],"source":"**SetText**: To change the text."},{"content":"Be careful if you use this because the pane will not automatically resize.","pos":[6982,7056]},{"content":"Refer to class <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>CStatusBar<ept id=\"p1\">](../mfc/reference/cstatusbar-class.md)</ept> in the <bpt id=\"p2\">*</bpt>Class Library Reference<ept id=\"p2\">*</ept> for details about <ph id=\"ph1\">`CStatusBar`</ph> creation and customization APIs.","pos":[7063,7225],"source":"Refer to class [CStatusBar](../mfc/reference/cstatusbar-class.md) in the *Class Library Reference* for details about `CStatusBar` creation and customization APIs."},{"content":"Most customization of status bars should be done before the status bar is initially made visible.","pos":[7226,7323]},{"content":"The status bar supports only one stretchy pane, usually the first pane.","pos":[7330,7401]},{"content":"The size of that pane is really a minimum size.","pos":[7402,7449]},{"content":"If the status bar is bigger than the minimum size of all the panes, any extra width will be given to the stretchy pane.","pos":[7450,7569]},{"content":"The default application with a status bar has right-aligned indicators for CAP, NUM and SCRL since the first pane is stretchy.","pos":[7570,7696]},{"pos":[7740,7748],"content":"CToolBar"},{"content":"A toolbar is a control bar with a row of bitmap buttons that may include separators.","pos":[7755,7839]},{"content":"Two styles of buttons are supported: pushbuttons and check box buttons.","pos":[7840,7911]},{"content":"Radio group functionality can be built with check box buttons and <ph id=\"ph1\">`ON_UPDATE_COMMAND_UI`</ph>.","pos":[7912,8001],"source":" Radio group functionality can be built with check box buttons and `ON_UPDATE_COMMAND_UI`."},{"content":"All the bitmap buttons in the toolbar are taken from one bitmap.","pos":[8008,8072]},{"content":"This bitmap must contain one image or glyph for each button.","pos":[8073,8133]},{"content":"Typically the order of the images/glyphs in the bitmap is the same order they will be drawn on the screen.","pos":[8134,8240]},{"content":"(This can be changed using the customization APIs.)","pos":[8241,8292]},{"content":"Each button must be the same size.","pos":[8299,8333]},{"content":"The default is the standard 24x22 pixels.","pos":[8334,8375]},{"content":"Each image/glyph must be the same size and must be side-by-side in the bitmap.","pos":[8376,8454]},{"content":"The default image/glyph size is 16x15 pixels.","pos":[8455,8500]},{"content":"Therefore, for a toolbar with 10 buttons (using standard sizes), you need a bitmap that is 160 pixels wide and 15 pixels high.","pos":[8501,8627]},{"content":"Each button has one and only one image/glyph.","pos":[8634,8679]},{"content":"The different button states and styles (for example, pressed, up, down, disabled, disabled down, indeterminate) are algorithmically generated from that one image/glyph.","pos":[8680,8848]},{"content":"Any color bitmap or DIB can be used in theory.","pos":[8849,8895]},{"content":"The algorithm for generating the different button states works best if the original image is shades of gray.","pos":[8896,9004]},{"content":"Look at the standard toolbar buttons and the toolbar button clipart provided in MFC General sample <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>CLIPART<ept id=\"p1\">](../visual-cpp-samples.md)</ept> for examples.","pos":[9005,9153],"source":" Look at the standard toolbar buttons and the toolbar button clipart provided in MFC General sample [CLIPART](../visual-cpp-samples.md) for examples."},{"content":"The colors used in the toolbar are also consistent with the recommendation of the Windows Interface Application Design Guide.","pos":[9160,9285]},{"content":"These colors are not hard coded and are changed dynamically in response to user customization in Control Panel.","pos":[9286,9397]},{"content":"Item","pos":[9404,9408]},{"content":"Windows COLOR value","pos":[9409,9428]},{"content":"Default RGB","pos":[9429,9440]},{"content":"ToolBar background","pos":[9504,9522]},{"content":"COLOR_BTNFACE","pos":[9525,9538]},{"content":"RGB(192,192,192)","pos":[9541,9557]},{"content":"ToolBar buttons top/left edges","pos":[9562,9592]},{"content":"COLOR_BTNHIGHLIGHT","pos":[9595,9613]},{"content":"RGB(255,255,255)","pos":[9616,9632]},{"content":"ToolBar buttons bot/right edges","pos":[9637,9668]},{"content":"COLOR_BTNSHADOW","pos":[9671,9686]},{"content":"RGB(128,128,128)","pos":[9689,9705]},{"content":"In addition, the toolbar bitmap buttons are recolored as though they were standard Windows button controls.","pos":[9713,9820]},{"content":"This recoloring occurs when the bitmap is loaded from the resource and in response to a change in system colors in response to user customization in Control Panel.","pos":[9821,9984]},{"content":"The following colors in a toolbar bitmap will be recolored automatically so they should be used with caution.","pos":[9985,10094]},{"content":"If you do not wish to have a portion of your bitmap recolored, then use a color that closely approximates one of the mapped RGB values.","pos":[10095,10230]},{"content":"The mapping is done based on exact RGB values.","pos":[10231,10277]},{"content":"RGB value","pos":[10284,10293]},{"content":"Dynamically mapped COLOR value","pos":[10294,10324]},{"content":"RGB(000, 000, 000)","pos":[10386,10404]},{"content":"COLOR_BTNTEXT","pos":[10405,10418]},{"content":"RGB(128, 128, 128)","pos":[10423,10441]},{"content":"COLOR_BTNSHADOW","pos":[10442,10457]},{"content":"RGB(192, 192, 192)","pos":[10462,10480]},{"content":"COLOR_BTNFACE","pos":[10481,10494]},{"content":"RGB(255, 255, 255)","pos":[10499,10517]},{"content":"COLOR_BTNHIGHLIGHT","pos":[10518,10536]},{"content":"Refer to class <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>CToolBar<ept id=\"p1\">](../mfc/reference/ctoolbar-class.md)</ept> the <bpt id=\"p2\">*</bpt>Class Library Reference<ept id=\"p2\">*</ept> for details about the <ph id=\"ph1\">`CToolBar`</ph> creation and customization APIs.","pos":[10544,10701],"source":"Refer to class [CToolBar](../mfc/reference/ctoolbar-class.md) the *Class Library Reference* for details about the `CToolBar` creation and customization APIs."},{"content":"Most customization of toolbars should be done before the toolbar is initially made visible.","pos":[10702,10793]},{"content":"The customization APIs can be used to adjust the button IDs, styles, spacer width and which image/glyph is used for what button.","pos":[10800,10928]},{"content":"By default you do not need to use these APIs.","pos":[10929,10974]},{"content":"CCmdUI Support for CToolBar","pos":[10983,11010]},{"content":"The way toolbar buttons are always updated is through the <ph id=\"ph1\">`ON_UPDATE_COMMAND_UI`</ph> mechanism.","pos":[11014,11105],"source":"The way toolbar buttons are always updated is through the `ON_UPDATE_COMMAND_UI` mechanism."},{"content":"On idle time, the toolbar will call the <ph id=\"ph1\">`ON_UPDATE_COMMAND_UI`</ph> handler with the command ID of that button.","pos":[11106,11212],"source":" On idle time, the toolbar will call the `ON_UPDATE_COMMAND_UI` handler with the command ID of that button."},{"content":"is not called for separators, but it is called for pushbuttons and check box buttons.","pos":[11236,11321]},{"pos":[11328,11372],"content":"The <ph id=\"ph1\">`ON_UPDATE_COMMAND_UI`</ph> handler can call:","source":"The `ON_UPDATE_COMMAND_UI` handler can call:"},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Enable<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>: To enable or disable the button.","pos":[11380,11424],"source":"**Enable**: To enable or disable the button."},{"content":"This works equally for pushbuttons and check box buttons.","pos":[11425,11482]},{"content":": To set the check state of a button.","pos":[11500,11537]},{"content":"Calling this for a toolbar button will turn it into a check box button.","pos":[11538,11609]},{"content":"takes a parameter which can be 0 (not checked), 1 (checked) or 2 (indeterminate)","pos":[11621,11701]},{"pos":[11719,11746],"content":": Shorthand for <ph id=\"ph1\">`SetCheck`</ph>.","source":": Shorthand for `SetCheck`."},{"content":"Check box buttons are \"AUTO\" check box buttons; that is, when the user presses them they will immediately change state.","pos":[11753,11872]},{"content":"Checked is the down or depressed state.","pos":[11873,11912]},{"content":"There is no built-in user interface way to change a button into the \"indeterminate\" state; that must be done through code.","pos":[11913,12035]},{"content":"The customization APIs will permit you to change the state of a given toolbar button, preferably you should change these states in the <ph id=\"ph1\">`ON_UPDATE_COMMAND_UI`</ph> handler for the command the toolbar button represents.","pos":[12042,12254],"source":"The customization APIs will permit you to change the state of a given toolbar button, preferably you should change these states in the `ON_UPDATE_COMMAND_UI` handler for the command the toolbar button represents."},{"content":"Remember, the idle processing will change the state of toolbar buttons with the <ph id=\"ph1\">`ON_UPDATE_COMMAND_UI`</ph> handler, so any changes to these states made through SetButtonStyle may get lost after the next idle.","pos":[12255,12459],"source":" Remember, the idle processing will change the state of toolbar buttons with the `ON_UPDATE_COMMAND_UI` handler, so any changes